// ch05 §5.12 + §5.3: a by-reference-capturing closure is a
// lifetime-tracked value exactly like a class holding a `T&` field --
// returning one out of the function whose local it captures must be
// rejected, since `local` is destroyed at `make_bad`'s exit while the
// returned closure would still hold a reference into it. Mirrors
// `function_returning_reference_with_no_reference_parameter_is_rejected`
// in 04_references_borrow, but the dangling reference is hidden inside a
// closure's member instead of being the function's literal return type.
//
// `auto` as a function's return type (return-type deduction) is the only
// way to spell a closure's own unnameable type as a return type, exactly
// as in real C++ -- assumed to already work like real C++ for the same
// reason noted in by_value_capture_snapshots_value_at_creation_not_call.
auto make_bad() {
    int local = 5;
    return [&local]() { return local; };
}

int main() {
    return 0;
}
